The steps in backprop
Now that you have worked through several nodes, we can write down the basic method:
working right to left, for each node:

calculate the local derivative(s) of the node
using the chain rule, combine with the derivative of the cost with respect to the node to the right.
The 'local derivative(s)' are the derivative(s) of the output of the current node with respect to all inputs or parameters.

Let's continue the job. We'll be a bit less verbose now that you are familiar with the method.

âˆ‚ğ½âˆ‚ğ‘
, âˆ‚ğ½âˆ‚ğ‘
The next node has two derivatives of interest. We need to calculate âˆ‚ğ½âˆ‚ğ‘
 so we can propagate to the left. We also want to calculate âˆ‚ğ½âˆ‚ğ‘
. Finding the derivative of the cost with respect to the parameters ğ‘¤
 and ğ‘
 is the object of backprop. We will find the local derivatives, âˆ‚ğ‘âˆ‚ğ‘
 and âˆ‚ğ‘âˆ‚ğ‘
 first and then combine those with the derivative coming from the right, âˆ‚ğ½âˆ‚ğ‘
.

# calculate the local derivatives da_dc, da_db
sa = sc + sb
sa
da_dc = diff(sa,sc)
da_db = diff(sa,sb)
print(da_dc, da_db)
dJ_dc = da_dc * dJ_da
dJ_db = da_db * dJ_da
print(f"dJ_dc = {dJ_dc},  dJ_db = {dJ_db}")
And in our example, d = 3

âˆ‚ğ½âˆ‚ğ‘¤
The last node in this example calculates c. Here, we are interested in how J changes with respect to the parameter w. We will not back propagate to the input ğ‘¥
, so we are not interested in âˆ‚ğ½âˆ‚ğ‘¥
. Let's start by calculating âˆ‚ğ‘âˆ‚ğ‘¤
.

# calculate the local derivative
sc = sw * sx
sc
dc_dw = diff(sc,sw)
dc_dw
This derivative is a bit more exciting than the last one. This will vary depending on the value of ğ‘¥
. This is 2 in our example.

Combine this with âˆ‚ğ½âˆ‚ğ‘
 to find âˆ‚ğ½âˆ‚ğ‘¤
.

dJ_dw = dc_dw * dJ_dc
dJ_dw
print(f"dJ_dw = {dJ_dw.subs([(sd,d),(sx,x)])}")
ğ‘‘=3
, so âˆ‚ğ½âˆ‚ğ‘¤=6
 for our example.
Let's test this arithmetically:

J_epsilon = ((w+0.001)*x+b - y)**2/2
k = (J_epsilon - J)/0.001  
print(f"J = {J}, J_epsilon = {J_epsilon}, dJ_dw ~= k = {k} ")
They match! Great. You can add âˆ‚ğ½âˆ‚ğ‘¤
